<p>Self-assigning work packages</p><p>During down time, self-assign a work package that is not yet
	 assigned. 
  </p> 
	  
		<p> 
		<ul> 
		  
			  Your role in the project must match the role
				required for the unassigned work packages. For instance, if a work package is
				waiting for an editor, but you are an author, the work package does not appear.
				
			  
			  Your role in
				the project must match the role required for the unassigned work packages. For
				instance, if a work package is waiting for an editor, but you are an author,
				the work package does not appear. 
			  
			  Your role
				in the project must match the role required for the unassigned work packages.
				For instance, if a work package is waiting for an editor, but you are an
				author, the work package does not appear. 
			  
			  Your role in
				the project must match the role required for the unassigned work packages. For
				example, if you are a reviewer, then you can only see work packages waiting for
				review. 
			  
		   
		 
		</ul> 
	 </p> 
		<p> There are times
		  when there might be a backlog of work packages waiting for an assignee. For
		  example, a lead writer can create multiple work packages, but not assign them.
		  If the first step in the work flow is authoring and you have the role of
		  author, then you can access the list of unassigned work packages and assign a
		  work package to yourself. 
		</p>
		<p> There are times when there might be a backlog of
		  work packages waiting for an assignee. For example, a lead writer can create
		  multiple work packages, but not assign them. If the first step in the work flow
		  is authoring and you have the role of author, then you can access the list of
		  unassigned work packages and assign a work package to yourself. 
		</p> 
		<p> There are
		  times when there might be a backlog of work packages waiting for an assignee.
		  For example, a lead writer can create multiple work packages, but not assign
		  them. If the first step in the work flow is authoring and you have the role of
		  author, then you can access the list of unassigned work packages and assign a
		  work package to yourself. 
		</p> 
		<p>There are times
		  when there might be a backlog of work packages waiting for an assignee. For
		  example, an author might complete multiple work packages, but instead of
		  assigning them to a specific reviewer, they are left as unassigned in the
		  review state. If the next step in the work flow is Review and you have the role
		  of reviewer, then you can access the list of unassigned work packages and
		  assign a work package to yourself. 
		</p> 
	  
	  
		 
		   Access 
			 My Work. 
		   
		 
		 
		  Click 
			 Display unassigned work packages. 
		   
		 
		 
		  Click 
			 Assign to me beside the work package on which
			 you want to work. 
		   
		 
	  
	  
		<p> The work package is assigned to you
		  and CORDAP sends you an assignment notification email. 
		</p> 
	  
  